Claims I Claim: 1. A method for autonomously navigating along a crosswalk comprising, at an autonomous vehicle: â¢ at a first time, navigating autonomously along a sidewalk toward a crosswalk at an intersection, the crosswalk coinciding with a navigation route assigned to the autonomous vehicle; â¢ recording optical data of a scene proximal the autonomous vehicle via an optical sensor integrated into the autonomous vehicle; â¢ aligning an anteroposterior axis of the autonomous vehicle to the crosswalk detected in the optical data; â¢ identifying a pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data; â¢ in response to the pedestrian entering the crosswalk at a second time succeeding the first time, predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection; and â¢ in response to predicting right of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection: o autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk; and o autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to an opposing sidewalk according to the navigation route. 2. The method of Claim l: â¢ further comprising identifying the crosswalk as an unprotected crosswalk based on an unprotected crosswalk label associated with the intersection in a navigation map; â¢ wherein identifying the pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises identifying the pedestrian occupying the sidewalk proximal the crosswalk in optical data recorded over a first period of time preceding the second time; â¢ further comprising, prior to the second time: o calculating a first confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection responsive to detecting the pedestrian stopped on the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk, the first confidence score less than a first threshold score; o in response to the first threshold score exceeding the first confidence score, halting on the sidewalk proximal the crosswalk; 

â¢ wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises calculating a second confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection responsive to detecting the pedestrian entering the crosswalk at the second time, the second confidence score exceeding the first confidence score; and â¢ wherein autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk comprises autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk in response to the second confidence score exceeding the first threshold score. 3. The method of Claim 2: â¢ further comprising detecting a vehicle approaching the intersection in optical data recorded over the first period of time; â¢ wherein calculating the first confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises calculating the first confidence score further as an inverse function of a velocity of the vehicle; â¢ further comprising detecting the vehicle slowing toward the crosswalk in optical data recorded over a second period of time succeeding the first period of time; and â¢ wherein calculating the second confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises calculating the second confidence score further as a function of the vehicle slowing toward the crosswalk. 4. The method of Claim 2, wherein autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to the opposing sidewalk comprises: â¢ navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk via a near ramp; â¢ autonomously following within a threshold distance of the pedestrian as the pedestrian moves through the crosswalk; â¢ veering from behind the pedestrian to a far ramp between the crosswalk and the opposing sidewalk; and â¢ autonomously navigating up the far ramp onto the opposing sidewalk. 5. The method of Claim 1: â¢ wherein identifying the pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises detecting the pedestrian occupying the opposing sidewalk proximal the crosswalk in optical data recorded over a first period of time preceding the second time; 

 further comprising, prior to the second time: o calculating a first confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based on the pedestrian stopped on the opposing sidewalk, the first confidence score less than a first threshold score; o in response to the first threshold score exceeding the first confidence score, halting on the sidewalk proximal the crosswalk; wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises calculating a second confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection as a function of the pedestrian entering the crosswalk and heading toward the autonomous vehicle and as an inverse function of a difference between a speed of the pedestrian and a predefined nominal pedestrian speed; and wherein autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk comprises autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk and past the pedestrian in response to the second confidence score exceeding the first threshold score. The method of Claim 1: wherein identifying the pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises detecting a group of pedestrians occupying the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk; wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection in response to detecting a subset of pedestrians, exceeding a threshold proportion of the group of pedestrians, entering the crosswalk together at approximately the second time; and wherein autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to the opposing sidewalk comprises following the subset of pedestrians across the crosswalk to the opposing sidewalk. The method of Claim l, further comprising: identifying a second pedestrian occupying a second crosswalk perpendicular to the crosswalk at approximately the second time; and in response to identifying the second pedestrian occupying the second crosswalk: 

 o withdrawing prediction of right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection; and o transmitting a query to a remote operator portal for manual confirmation to enter the intersection. 8. The method of Claim 1: â¢ further comprising determining that the intersection is populated with a lighted traffic signal based on a traffic signal label associated with the intersection in a navigation map; â¢ scanning the optical data for the lighted traffic signal to determine right of way at the intersection; â¢ wherein identifying the pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises, in response to obstruction of the lighted traffic signal in a field of view of the optical sensor, scanning the optical data for pedestrians proximal a location of the crosswalk indicated in the navigation map; â¢ wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises: o predicting lack of right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based on presence of the pedestrian on the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk prior to the second time; and o predicting possession of right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based on presence of the pedestrian in the crosswalk at the second time. 9. The method of Claim 1: â¢ wherein identifying a pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises: o scanning the scene proximal the autonomous vehicle for pedestrians; o detecting the pedestrian occupying the sidewalk proximal the crosswalk in optical data recorded by the optical sensor over a period of time preceding the second time; and o calculating an angular yaw offset between the pedestrian and the crosswalk; â¢ wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises: 

 o predicting an intent of the pedestrian to enter the crosswalk as a function of a duration of the period of time and as an inverse function of the angular yaw offset; and o associating right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection with entry of the pedestrian into the crosswalk in response to the intent of the pedestrian to enter the crosswalk exceeding a threshold intent. The method of Claim 1: wherein navigating autonomously along the sidewalk comprises autonomously navigating toward and slowing upon approach to a region of the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk; and wherein autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk comprises autonomously navigating continuously from the sidewalk into the crosswalk in response to detecting the pedestrian entering the crosswalk and predicting right of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection accordingly prior to arrival of the autonomous vehicle at the region of the sidewalk. The method of Claim 1: wherein predicting right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection comprises calculating a confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based on presence of the pedestrian in the crosswalk that intersects the navigation route of the autonomous vehicle; further comprising, in response to the confidence score exceeding a first threshold score: o transmitting a query to a remote operator portal for manual confirmation to enter the intersection; o transmitting a portion of the scan data to the remote operator portal; and o holding at the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk; and wherein autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk comprises autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk in response to the confidence score exceeding the first threshold score and upon receipt of confirmation entered manually by a remote human operator at the remote operator portal. 12. The method of Claim 11, further comprising, in response to receipt of rejection to enter the intersection from the remote human operator via the remote operator portal: â¢ remaining at the sidewalk adjacent the crosswalk; â¢ calculating a revised confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based on features detected in optical data recorded at a third time succeeding the second time; and â¢ in response to the revised confidence score exceeding a second threshold score, transmitting a second query to the remote operator portal for manual confirmation to enter the intersection, the second threshold score exceeding the first threshold score. 13. The method of Claim 11: â¢ wherein recording optical data of the scene comprises recording a color video feed of the scene proximal the autonomous vehicle via a color camera integrated into the autonomous vehicle; and â¢ wherein transmitting the portion of the scan data to the remote operator portal comprises: o querying a navigation map for a georeferenced area of interest associated with the intersection; o cropping frames in the color video feed around the georeferenced region of interest; and o transmitting cropped frames in the color video feed to a remote computer system, via wireless communication protocol, for distribution to the remote operator portal. 14. A method for autonomously navigating along a crosswalk comprising, at an autonomous vehicle: â¢ navigating autonomously along a sidewalk toward a crosswalk at an intersection, the crosswalk coinciding with a navigation route assigned to the autonomous vehicle; â¢ recording optical data of a scene proximal the autonomous vehicle via an optical sensor integrated into the autonomous vehicle; â¢ aligning an anteroposterior axis of the autonomous vehicle to the crosswalk detected in the optical data; 

â¢ at a first time, calculating a first confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the crosswalk based on proximity of a vehicle detected proximal the intersection in the scan data; â¢ at a second time succeeding the first time, identifying a pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data; â¢ in response to the pedestrian entering the crosswalk, calculating a second confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the crosswalk based on presence of the pedestrian in the crosswalk, the second confidence score greater than the first confidence score; â¢ in response to the second confidence score exceeding a first threshold score, transmitting a query to a remote operator portal to confirm entry of the autonomous vehicle into the crosswalk; and â¢ in response to confirmation to enter the crosswalk from the remote operator portal: o autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk; and o autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to an opposing sidewalk according to the navigation route. 15. The method of Claim 14: â¢ wherein transmitting the query to the remote operator portal to confirm entry of the autonomous vehicle into the crosswalk comprises transmitting the query to the remote operator portal in response to the confidence score exceeding the first threshold score and in response to a second threshold score exceeding the confidence score; and â¢ further comprising, in response to the confidence score exceeding the first threshold score and the second threshold score: o withholding the query to the remote operator portal; o autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk; and o autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to the opposing sidewalk according to the navigation route. 16. The method of Claim 14: â¢ wherein recording optical data of the scene comprises recording a color video feed of the scene proximal the autonomous vehicle via a color camera integrated into the autonomous vehicle; and 

â¢ querying a navigation map for a georeferenced area of interest associated with the intersection; â¢ cropping frames in the color video feed around the georeferenced region of interest; and â¢ transmitting cropped frames in the color video feed to a remote computer system, via wireless communication protocol, for distribution to the remote operator portal. 17. The method of Claim 14, wherein calculating the second confidence score comprises calculating the second confidence score: â¢ proportional to a size and a density of a group of pedestrians detected in the crosswalk at approximately the second time; â¢ inversely proportional to a detected speed of the group of pedestrians moving across the crosswalk at approximately the second time; â¢ inversely proportional to a number of pedestrians moving across a second crosswalk perpendicular to the crosswalk at approximately the second time; and â¢ inversely proportional to speeds of vehicles approaching the intersection perpendicular to the crosswalk at approximately the second time. 18. The method of Claim 14: â¢ wherein identifying the pedestrian proximal the intersection in the optical data comprises identifying the pedestrian occupying the sidewalk proximal the crosswalk; and â¢ wherein autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to the opposing sidewalk comprises: o navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk via a near ramp; o autonomously following within a threshold distance of the pedestrian across the crosswalk; and o veering from behind the pedestrian to a far ramp between the crosswalk and the opposing sidewalk; and o autonomously navigating up the far ramp onto the opposing sidewalk. 19. A method for autonomously navigating along a crosswalk comprising, at an autonomous vehicle: â¢ navigating autonomously along a sidewalk toward a crosswalk at an intersection, the crosswalk coinciding with a navigation route assigned to the autonomous vehicle; 

 recording optical data of a scene proximal the autonomous vehicle via an optical sensor integrated into the autonomous vehicle; aligning an anteroposterior axis of the autonomous vehicle to the crosswalk detected in the optical data; at a first time, detecting states of lighted traffic signals, proximal the intersection, in the optical data; at approximately the first time, calculating a velocity of a vehicle approaching the intersection; calculating a confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection based states of lighted traffic signals proximal the intersection and the velocity of the vehicle; in response to the confidence score exceeding a threshold score, transmitting a query to a remote operator portal to confirm entry of the autonomous vehicle into the crosswalk; and in response to confirmation to enter the crosswalk from the remote operator portal: o autonomously navigating from the sidewalk into the crosswalk; and o autonomously navigating along the crosswalk to an opposing sidewalk according to the navigation route. The method of Claim 19, further comprising: identifying a pedestrian, proximal the intersection at approximately the first time, in the optical data; and in response to the pedestrian entering the crosswalk at a second time succeeding the first time, increasing the confidence score for right of way of the autonomous vehicle to enter the intersection.
